******
[2] USA ex Netherlands
Date: Tue 2 Oct 2012
Source: NY Daily News, Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.nydailynews.com/life-style/health/smoked-salmon-blamed-salmonella-outbreak-u-s-netherlands-article-1.1172681


Smoked salmon tainted with salmonellae has sickened hundreds of people in the Netherlands and the USA, sparking a major recall, health authorities said Tue 2 Oct 2012.

The National Institute for Public Health and the Environment said the salmon has been traced to Dutch company Foppen, which sells fish to many major Dutch supermarkets and to stores around the world, including the United States.

Foppen company spokesman Bart de Vries said that since the company set up a public information phone 2 two days ago 30 Sep 2012], some 1400 people had called and around 350 of the callers "reported symptoms consistent with a salmonellosis."

De Vries said that in the USA the company sells only to wholesaler Costco and that Costco would deal with any USA recall. It was not immediately clear how much contaminated fish had been sold in USA. A message left at Costco's headquarters before office hours was not immediately returned.

Roel Vincken of the Dutch Food and Consumer Product Safety Authority, which carried out tests confirming the salmonella outbreak, said he had no information on a USA recall.

De Vries said the company did not believe contaminated fish had been sold to any other countries.

Foppen, which processes fish in the Netherlands and at a factory in Greece, is investigating the cause of the outbreak. "The investigation into the cause is under way and has been narrowed down to one production line at one factory (in Greece)," De Vries told The Associated Press. "We can't yet say what the cause of the infection was."

Foppen has halted all production of smoked salmon until the investigation is completed, he added.

